LETTER FROM THE SUPERINTENDENT: Please click the link below to read a letter from Dr. Aaron Johnson about recent events. "Although our immediate focus is on safely reopening our schools amid a pandemic, I am compelled to address the turmoil on our doorstep. Personally and professionally, I feel a deep sense of sorrow and heartache about the death of Daniel Prude and the division in Rochester and our surrounding areas. As superintendent, I am responsible for coordinating a reaction in support of our students, families and staff and am searching for the right way to go about it."

Full letter: üëâ http://bit.ly/WI_Supt_Letter

REOPENING REPORT #9: "I remember what my parents would tell me when I was a student and felt a little under the weather; they‚Äôd say to do my best to get through the day," Superintendent, Aaron Johnson, writes in today's report. "That isn't the case anymore. Students and staff must check their signs and symptoms daily and commit to STAYING HOME if there's any reason they think they're sick. That's a pledge we must make to each other. Together, we can and will ensure our collective health." Click below to read his full update on masking, daily health screens and more:

http://bit.ly/REOPENING_REPORT

CAPITAL PROJECT UPDATE: One noticeable change for visitors to IHS and Dake Jr. HS is a new security vestibule inside the main entrance of each foyer. That‚Äôs where our staff will check in visitors using the Raptor system we introduced to start last school year. Reminder: If you put your license/Photo ID in the system last year, it carries over. These additional security layers were part of the Capital Project approved by our 2018 District Vote. Construction work is being completed this week in preparation for the first day of school on Thursday, Sept. 10th.

Dake‚Äôs main office underwent a massive renovation, too, including relocating the main office a little closer to the main entrance. The gymnasium at IHS, complete with a new hardwood floor and video scoreboard, is also near completion. To see more updates, click the link: http://bit.ly/WICap_Project

post_text: STATEMENT FROM THE SUPERINTENDENT: Today, I was asked to join the Bob Lonsberry radio show on WHAM-AM 1180 to share our perspective on school reopening. As in other invitations to participate in radio and television, I saw this as an opportunity to share more insight into our plans to keep our students and families well-informed. I do not follow Mr. Lonsberry on Twitter and after joining his show, was given his most recent post by a concerned community member. The West Irondequoit Central School District and I do not support or endorse Mr. Lonsberry's views and want to clarify that the purpose today was to share our information. I can see how my participation is being viewed as support of his actions and words. This is not the case.

post_text:
JOIN THE DISCUSSION ON RACISM: The Town of Irondequoit, East Irondequoit & West Irondequoit schools and Irondequoit Public Library have partnered for a community-wide book discussion on the history of racism. They'll provide community members e-book, downloadable audio books and print copes of "STAMPED: Racism, Antiracism and You," by Ibram X. Kendi and Jason Reynolds. This is a young readers‚Äô adaptation of Kendi‚Äôs award-winning book. The partnership will organize book discussions in small groups with students, their families and all interested residents. The goal: Facilitate conversations that will foster a better understanding of racism and how to change structural racism and barriers to equality.

Spots are limited. Register at this link: https://bit.ly/2Zckyek

JOIN THE DISCUSSION ON RACISM: The Town of Irondequoit, East Irondequoit & West Irondequoit schools and Irondequoit Public Library have partnered for a community-wide book discussion on the history of racism. They'll provide community members e-book, downloadable audio books and print copes of "STAMPED: Racism, Antiracism and You," by Ibram X. Kendi and Jason Reynolds. This is a young readers‚Äô adaptation of Kendi‚Äôs award-winning book. The partnership will organize book discussions in small groups with students, their families and all interested residents. The goal: Facilitate conversations that will foster a better understanding of racism and how to change structural racism and barriers to equality.

Register at this link: https://bit.ly/2Zckyek

post_text: DAKE SCHOOL AWARDS CITIZENSHIP HONORS: For 25-plus years, the Ira J. Jacobson Auxiliary Post # 474 in Greece has awarded the Dake Junior High School Citizenship Awards to two deserving 8th graders. The winners were Catherine Bondi and Ryan Boudreau, who each received the award by a vote of Dake faculty/staff. Criteria for this honor includes attributes such as respectfulness to others, courteous attitude, leadership qualities, reliability and compassion. Dake Principal Michelle Cramer made the presentation on Monday of a check from the Post, an official certificate of honor from the Auxiliary and a flag that has been flown over the U.S. Capitol Building. Post leader, Mrs. Mickey Darrohn of Greece, arranged for these awards to be presented to these deserving students.

TRACK REOPENS; HOURS EXTENDED FOR FIELDS: The Irondequoit High School track reopened Thursday morning, two days ahead of schedule following routine cleaning and maintenance. The West Irondequoit CSD is also extending the hours of operation for the stadium (turf) field and baseball and softball diamonds. Starting Friday, June 19th, those facilities will now be open daily from 7 a.m. to 8 p.m. In accordance with past practice, the turf field will not be on open for weekend use.

Social distancing should still be practiced. Please note that any unauthorized, organized team activities or competitions are not permitted. Finally and in accordance with state reopening guidelines, groups larger than 25 are not allowed. Thank you for your cooperation.

post_text: OUTDOOR EDUCATION - Those two words are, in a way, a rite of passage for West Irondequoit sixth-graders. It's one of their last big events before Iroquois and Rogers middle school students take their next step to junior high. Our students learn a variety of tasks during Outdoor Education, which has taken place for decades at Camp Cutler in Naples, southeast of Rochester. Due to COVID-19 and like everything else these days, Outdoor Ed looks different this year. It's happening via our computer screens. Our educators have made several "How-To" videos to engage with our students, so the tradition of Outdoor Ed continues. Here's Rogers Math and Science Teacher Steve Brickler showing students different areas in West Irondequoit where they can go to hike.

'REMEMBER THE LOVE' CONCERT SATURDAY: IHS senior and musical standout, Elijah Culp, has been organizing a yearly benefit concert called "Remember the Love." It was created in honor of Michael Lynch, an IHS student who in 2017 was struck by a car on his way to school and passed away. Featuring students from across the Rochester area, the concert raises money for "Classic Michael Lynch," which gives money to college-bound seniors who have participated in community theater. The virtual event this year 7 PM TOMORROW (Saturday, 6/6).

Here's the link to the event::
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GyZAW--1lks

Says Cup: "If you're like me and a bit overwhelmed by everything that has been going on in the world lately, then this concert is for you. Everyone has been working hard to put together this concert and create something that brings a little bit of comfort into our lives at a time like this when we need it the most."

To watch a video profile of Culp, click here: https://www.westirondequoit.org/cms/one.aspx?portalId=228594&pageId=89649640

post_text: REOPENING MONDAY! Irondequoit High School's stadium (turf) field and its baseball and softball diamonds will reopen starting Monday, June 8th at 7 a.m. They will be open Monday through Friday from 7 a.m. to 1 p.m. In accordance with guidance from the state, social distancing should still be practiced. This is being done with the community in mind. Organized, team activities or competitions and groups over 10 will not be permitted. Thank you for your cooperation as we continue to do what is necessary for safe facility use by all. The IHS tennis courts recently re-opened. The track and grass field has remained open for community use throughout our building's closure.

WRITING CONTEST/4 DAYS LEFT! Do you want a chance for your story to be featured in Chaz Bruce‚Äôs video for IPL? Here‚Äôs how to enter! Write a story‚Äîup to two pages‚Äîthat encourages reading while including the words:

Phone
Pizza
Plants
Pants

The story can be words, pictures, or a combination of both. The contest is open to kids and teens up to age 18. Younger participants may enlist the help of an adult caregiver, as long as the ideas and wording belong to the participant. Email your completed story to: Amy.Holland@libraryweb.org by THIS FRIDAY, June 5th, 2020. Chaz Bruce will read the winning entry at the beginning of his summer reading video for IPL. Other outstanding entries may be featured on IPL‚Äôs social media and/or website.

Good luck, and happy writing!
